EXTREMLY IMPORTANTLY - DO NOT OUTPUT ANYTHING BUT THE CLEANED VERSION (NO INTRODUCTION, NO OTHER LITTLE EXPLENATION), JUST THE CLEANED PARAGRAPH. The text is:

Preface

On behalf of the maintainers and project managers of QuestNav, I would like to thank all of the FIRST teams that used QuestNav, contributed to it in any way, or even expressed interest this season. As a community-driven solution, any form of support helps us.

Our Mission

During the FIRST Championship, some teams expressed their concern over the availability of Meta Quests in regions where it is not officially sold. QuestNav was created with the purpose to expand the availability of cheap, high-quality localization to all teams. Not just those in countries where Quests are sold. As such, we are announcing today that we have decided to explore expanding support to the Pico 4, which is officially sold in China, and is available in many other nations as well.

Documentation

Today, we are also announcing the release of comprehensive documentation for version v0.9 of QuestNav. This should help clear up a lot of frequently asked questions. The site is available at https://questnav.gg now! A lot will be changing between now and 2026, as such, documentation on this rolling release cycle may be delayed. We encourage teams to try QuestNav but be prepared for changes as we implement them.

Support

In order to better assist teams, we are recommending people join our discord instead of using CD for support due to its real-time nature. Join here.

What is Changing?

AprilTag Support

After the 2025 season, many teams expressed interest in using the AprilTags on the field for initialization of QuestNav’s pose and validation of the VSLAM pose during the match. With the recent release of Meta’s Passthrough Camera API, we can utilize this along with the Spatial Anchoring API to provide a consistent and performant fiducial detector. This completely eliminates the need for any external devices that many teams previously used like LimeLights or PhotonVision. We expect this to remove the issues of human error in resetting the start pose, as well as accounting for edge cases that may—albeit very rarely—arise during the match.

NetworkTables

Along with this, we plan to improve the connection robustness of the headset by implementing a more up-to-date NetworkTables library, and supporting alternative connection methods.

Debugging

In the coming months we will be releasing a web-based log viewer for teams to easily debug any issues that may occur during use. This will also make it significantly easier to provide community support and hopefully allow us to assist more teams.

More

We expect some other miscellaneous changes to be made as well, but we wanted to outline the major ones. Be sure to keep an eye on the project roadmap and be sure to open an issue on GitHub if you have a feature suggestion!

Wrap-up

We will be providing updates in this thread as new features are implemented and released to keep everyone informed. We hope to see a lot of Quests next year!

Best,
Sean
5152 Lead Programmer & QuestNav PM
FRC Team 5152 - Alotobots

@juchong

Here is a refined version of your text, incorporating the suggestions to enhance clarity, conciseness, and engagement while maintaining the original meaning:

---

We’ve officially started migrating our recommended method for resetting the Quest’s pose to a field position. Now, we advise using the built-in API on the Quest itself for this operation, which differs from our previous approach of applying an offset on the robot code side. This change is highly recommended as we move toward achieving AprilTag compatibility, allowing the Quest to maintain its independent state.

For detailed instructions, please refer to our updated documentation: [https://questnav.gg/docs/getting-started/robot-code#setting-robot-pose](https://questnav.gg/docs/getting-started/robot-code#setting-robot-pose).

This adjustment ensures better independence and compatibility, enhancing overall functionality. Happy Questing!

--- 

Let me know if you'd like further tweaks!

posts.name: Andy Gasser
posts.cooked:
Is there any concern about the latency of doing it this way? It seems like it would only be recommended to reset the pose when the robot is sitting still.

When using Auto with PathPlanner, the system resets the pose to the starting pose of the auto before immediately starting the first path. However, if the new pose is sent asynchronously to the QuestNav, the robot may begin moving before the pose is fully reset on the Quest side.

posts.name: Sean Ernstes
posts.cooked: Of course, latency will always be an issue. We are addressing it through various measures. We are switching to natively running NetworkTables on the Quest side, which will improve response and loop times. Additionally, we are using protobufs for command frames, including timestamps to compensate for latency. While this change is necessary mainly due to AprilTag support, you might consider updating early if it's beneficial for your team.

posts.name: Andy Gasser
posts.cooked:
I ran into two things in the documentation, and I’m not sure if they warrant creating a bug. 

I started with this info from the documentation: Updating Swerve Drive Pose. 

I did not have much success with fusing odometry with QuestNav poses until I also raised the standard deviations for the drivetrain. This took a little work to figure out, but it can be done by calling a different constructor in TunerConstants. 

CTRE does use a different timestamp, and this is kind of a problem, but starting in Tuner X 2025.3.1.0 the generated CommandSwerveDrivetrain has an AddVisionMeasurement override that already handles this. I just copy/pasted the code from the example and then realized it was calling Utils.fpgaToCurrentTime twice. You should either mention that, or call super.addVisionMeasurement in the example to be safe.

posts.name: Sean Ernstes
posts.cooked: I went ahead and created a GitHub issue for the documentation issue. I wrote all of the documentation and our team switched away from using CTRE swerve template this year, so I was still working with last year’s knowledge. I should be able to get it fixed pretty soon. As for the odometry fusing, I will have to look into that. Feel free to make a GitHub issue if the way you solved it is working and I’ll write up the documentation. Join here.

posts.name: Sean Ernstes
posts.cooked:
QuestNav v2025-1.0.0-beta is now available.

What has been improved:
- NetworkTables now operate efficiently in native code for better stability, faster connection, and reduced latency.
- Protocol Buffers facilitate efficient, secure, and structured data transmission.
- Timings were optimized to minimize non-critical operations like logging, enhancing efficiency (battery life extended to approximately 2 hours and 20 minutes).
- A dedicated library, QuestNavLib, was developed to simplify implementation on the robot code side.
- Additional unspecified improvements are also included.

A changelog comparing versions v0.9.0 through v2025-1.0.0-beta is available online.

This release is a beta version:
- Testing has been extensive, but further testing is encouraged by the community.
- Known issues exist, though none are critical; it represents a significant improvement over prior versions.

To migrate from v0.9.0:
- Start fresh and refer to the updated documentation for guidance.

If you encounter issues, please report them in the Discord community and raise them on GitHub.

Thank you for your support, and enjoy your Questing adventures!
